  <\definition>
    A linear map d : A \<rightarrow\> A is called a derivation if d(ab) = ad(b) + bd(a) for all a,b \<in\> A. We denote the set of all derivations by Der(A).
  </definition>

  <\exercise>
    Show that for vector space <math|K<around*|[|x|]>>, Der(A) \ = {<math|h<around*|(|x|)>\<cdot\><frac|d|d x> >\|<math|h<around*|(|x|)>\<in\>K<around*|[|x|]>>}

    <\solution*>
      By the definition, <math|d<around*|(|1|)>=d<around*|(|1\<times\>1|)>=2d<around*|(|1|)>.> Hence <math|d<around*|(|1|)>=0.>

      Let <math|d<around*|(|x|)>=h<around*|(|x|)>.>

      By mathematics induction, we can say for <math|deg>(<math|f>) \<leq\> <math|n>, this holds.

      Witout loss of generality, we can assume <math|f<around*|(|x|)>= <easypolynpls1>>.

      <math|d<around*|(|f<around*|(|x|)>|)>=d<around*|(|x<around*|(|a<rsub|n+1>x<rsup|n>+a<rsub|n>x<rsup|n-1>+1|)>|)>=h<around*|(|x|)><around*|(|<around*|(|n+1|)>a<rsub|n+1>x<rsup|n-1>+<around*|(|n-1|)>a<rsub|n>x<rsup|n-2>+\<cdots\>a<rsub|1>|)>+h<around*|(|x|)>f<around*|(|x|)>=h<around*|(|x|)><frac|d f<around*|(|x|)>|d x>.>

      \;
    </solution*>
  </exercise>

